You can use a single XSL file as an alternative by passing it as a parameter. For example, when building XHTML content, XSL parameters allow the user to specify a separate local XSL file (inside or outside the toolbox) to be called instead of the default XHTML code. Typically, this code imports the default processing code and overrides several processing routines. This method is best when the coverage is very small or the style varies from build to build. However, any extensions made using such overlays can also be implemented through plugins.  Creating a plug-in can be very simple or very complex, and is usually the best way to change or extend the toolbox. Plugins can be used to complete almost all the modifications required for toolbox processing, from smaller style adjustments to extensive, complex new output formats.  It is strongly recommended not to edit DITA-OT code directly. Modifying the code directly will greatly increase the work and risks involved in future upgrades. Such modifications are also likely to break plugins provided by others, limiting the toolkit's available functionality. "range": {
      "begin": [
        {"type":"INF_MIN"},  //
        {"type":"INT", "value":"0"}  //
      ], 
      "end": [
        {"type":"INF_MAX"}, //。
        {"type":"INT", "value":"9999"} //
      ]
